# Blender 4.5 AI Assistant Add-on — Architecture Guide

## Project Structure

```
blender_ai_assistant/
├── __init__.py              # bl_info, dep bootstrap, register/unregister
├── preferences.py           # AddonPreferences: API keys, model, safety flags
├── operators/
│   └── __init__.py          # All bpy.types.Operator subclasses + AddonState
├── panels/
│   └── __init__.py          # All bpy.types.Panel subclasses (N-panel UI)
├── utils/
│   ├── __init__.py
│   ├── ai_client.py         # HTTP wrapper for Claude / OpenAI / Ollama
│   ├── sandbox.py           # AST scanner + restricted exec sandbox
│   └── scene_context.py     # Scene → JSON serialiser
└── assets/
    └── example_prompts.py   # Reference AI-generated code snippets
```

---

## 1. Add-on Architecture

### Registration Flow

```
Blender startup
  └─ __init__.register()
       ├─ preferences.register()     ← always registered (even if deps missing)
       ├─ operators.register()       ← registers OT classes + bpy.types.Scene props
       └─ panels.register()          ← registers PT classes in VIEW_3D sidebar
```

### State Management

Blender operators are **stateless** — they are instantiated fresh for every call.
Shared mutable state lives in `operators.AddonState`, a plain Python class
instance (`STATE`) stored at module level.  Blender's property system
(`bpy.types.Scene.*`) is used only for properties that need to appear in the UI.

### Threading Model

```
Main Thread (Blender)            Background Thread
─────────────────────            ────────────────────────────────────────────
AI_OT_send_prompt.execute()
  STATE.is_running = True
  thread.start()          ──────▶  _worker()
                                     client.chat(history)   # blocks on HTTP
  return {"FINISHED"}                …response arrives…
                                     bpy.app.timers.register(_back)
                          ◀──────
_back()  (main thread, via timer)
  STATE.is_running = False
  update scene properties
  tag_redraw()
```

`bpy.app.timers.register(fn, first_interval=0.05)` is the **only** safe way
to call bpy APIs from a background thread.  All other bpy calls from a
non-main thread will crash Blender.

